planations are incomplete. Political scientist Jason Seawright argues that party-system collapse is motivated fundamentally by voter anger at the traditional political parties, which is produced by corruption scandals and failures of representation. Integrating economic, organizational, and individual considerations, Seawright provides a new explanation and compelling new evidence to present a fuller picture of voters' decisions and actions in bringing about party-system collapse, and the rise of important outsider political leaders in South America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aElectionsxPeru. 0aElectionsxVenezuela. 0aElectionszPeru. 0aElectionszVenezuela. 0aPolitical partiesxPeru. 0aPolitical partiesxVenezuela. 0aPolitical partieszPeru. 0aPolitical partieszVenezuela. 0aVotingxPeru. 0aVotingxVenezuela. 0aVotingzPeru. 0aVotingzVenezuela. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804783927zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804783927.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles